{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"career":[{"role":"Deacon","organization":"Lee Congregational Church","start_year":1812,"end_year":1839},{"role":"Selectman","organization":"Lee, Massachusetts"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"character","header":"He cut down his own orchard","body":"Finding that too many neighbors were getting drunk on his cider, Deacon Ingersoll felled every apple tree on his farm except those that fed his own table. At seventy-five he traveled to Ohio and Michigan to visit his children — before the railroads, “in the days of rugged constitutions.”"},{"number":2,"category":"business","header":"His quarry is in the Capitol","body":"The marble quarry on his Lee farm, a mile and a half from the Congregational church he helped found, supplied “much of the marble in the Capitol in Washington.” The Ingersoll and Yale families, the genealogy says, “might well be called the founders of Lee.”"}],"slug":"david-ingersoll-1759"},"H00907":{"id":"H00907","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1760},"death":{"year":1837},"parents":{"father_id":"X00536","mother_id":"H00376"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00543","children_ids":["HD1690","HD1691","HD1692","HD1693","HD1694","HD1695","HD1696"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1781,"date_month":12,"date_day":18,"location_city":"Lee","location_state":"Massachusetts"}],"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","entry":"907"},{"short":"The Jonathan Edwards Collection (Yale)"},{"short":"Avery, Genealogy of the Ingersoll Family in America (1926)"},{"short":"Descendants of William Smith of Glastonbury CT (archive.org)","url":"https://archive.org/details/descendantsofwil00smit/page/38/mode/2up?q=Eunice+"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Genealogy of the Ingersoll Family in America 1926"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Sarah Parsons","first_name":"Sarah","last_name":"Parsons","married_names":["Ingersoll"]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Thirteen children all reached adulthood and married","body":"Sarah Parsons married Deacon David Ingersoll II at Stockbridge MA on December 13, 1781. Their thirteen children all grew to adulthood, married, and mostly had large families — over 2,000 descendants are recorded. The Ingersoll-Yale lineage was one of the founding strata of Lee, Massachusetts; the marble from David's farm quarry helped build the U.S. Capitol."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Two thousand descendants and counting","body":"The thirteen children she raised at Lee all married and “mostly had large families” — over two thousand descendants recorded by the 1926 Ingersoll genealogy, among them the founders of the Ingersoll Dollar Watch. Her widowed mother, a daughter of Jonathan Edwards, lived out years under her roof."}],"slug":"sarah-parsons-1760"},"X00536":{"id":"X00536","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_thomas_spouse":true},"birth":{"year":1719},"death":{"year":1785},"tags":["revolutionary_war"],"sources":[],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"H00376","children_ids":["H00901","H00902","H00903","H00904","H00905","H00906","H00907","H00908","H00909","H00910","H00911"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1750,"date_month":6,"date_day":11}],"gender":"male","parents":{},"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Revolutionary militia private; son-in-law of Jonathan Edwards","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elihu_Parsons_(politician)","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Elihu Parsons","first_name":"Elihu","last_name":"Parsons","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"military","header":"He marched in the Berkshire County militia","body":"Elihu Parsons served as a private in the Berkshire County militia during the Revolution, under Captain Ezra Whittlesey and Colonel John Brown. He is recognized as a patriot ancestor by the Daughters of the American Revolution.","number":1},{"category":"marriage","header":"He married a daughter of Jonathan Edwards","body":"In 1750 Parsons wed Sarah Edwards, a daughter of the theologian Jonathan Edwards, and the couple raised eleven children at Stockbridge. He lived as an esquire in the western Massachusetts hills.","number":2}],"slug":"elihu-parsons-1719"},"H00376":{"id":"H00376","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":5,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1728,"month":8,"day":25,"city":"Northampton","state":"Massachusetts"},"death":{"year":1805,"month":5,"day":15,"city":"Goshen","state":"Massachusetts"},"parents":{"father_id":"X00128","mother_id":"HD0418"},"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 376"},{"label":"Salt of the Earth — David Brainerd and Jerusha Edwards: A Colonial Love Story","url":"https://salt-ofthe-earth.blogspot.com/2013/02/david-brainerd-and-jerusha-edwards.html"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00536","children_ids":["H00901","H00902","H00903","H00904","H00905","H00906","H00907","H00908","H00909","H00910","H00911"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1750,"date_month":6,"date_day":11}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","notes":"The coincidence of two daughters marrying two Ingersolls in the same period and region (Berkshire County MA) likely reflects the prominence of the Ingersoll family in that area. (DAR records; FindAGrave)","related_id":"H00905","display_label":"Daughter Lydia married Aaron Ingersoll of Berkshire","link_text":"Lydia Parsons Ingersoll"},{"type":"family_connection","notes":"The coincidence of two daughters marrying two Ingersolls in the same period and region (Berkshire County MA) likely reflects the prominence of the Ingersoll family in that area. (DAR records; FindAGrave)","related_id":"H00907","display_label":"Daughter Sarah married David Ingersoll of Berkshire","link_text":"Sarah Parsons"}],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"bio":{"display_name":"Sarah Edwards","first_name":"Sarah","maiden_name":"Edwards","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777406086/sarahedwardsparsons_jcxgr0.png","photo_notes":"Sarah Edwards Parsons (1728-1805), eldest daughter of Jonathan Edwards."},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Eldest Edwards child born Sabbath afternoon, 1728","body":"She was born August 25, 1728 in Northampton — 'on a Sabbath day, between 2 and 3 o'clock in the afternoon,' as her father Jonathan Edwards recorded. She was the eldest of his eleven children."},{"number":2,"category":"marriage","header":"Married her father's attorney — Stockbridge farmer","body":"In 1750 she married Elihu Parsons, a Northampton attorney who handled many of Jonathan Edwards's legal and personal affairs. Parsons later farmed in Stockbridge, where the family settled during the Mohican mission years."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Father warned suitor of her temper","body":"When Elihu Parsons asked Jonathan Edwards for her hand, Edwards reportedly disclosed her difficult temper before quipping: 'I hope she has grace, but grace can live where you cannot.'"},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Two daughters married into the Berkshire Ingersolls","body":"Two of her eleven children — both daughters — married into the Ingersoll family of Berkshire County, Massachusetts. This is a separate Ingersoll line from the Loyalist New Haven Ingersolls who descended through the Newton-Miles line."}],"slug":"sarah-edwards-1728"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}